  "title": "The Influence of Pain and Stress on Sleep in Children With Sickle Cell Disease",
  "abstract": "Abstract This study explored the relation among pain, stress, and sleep in 24 children with sickle cell disease aged 8 to 12 years. Children and their parents completed a baseline assessment of the children's pain, stress, and sleep. Following the baseline assessment, children completed a daily diary assessing these variables for up to 8 weeks. Children's baseline sleep reports appeared fairly consistent with their parents' reports and the children's daily diaries. Results from regression models indicated that high pain severity was related to poor sleep quality and that this relation was exacerbated at higher levels of stress. Understanding the way in which pain and stress relate to sleep may lead to improved symptom management in pediatric populations. ACKNOWLEDGMENT This research was supported by National Institutes of Health Grant R01 HL62172, with Karen M. Gil as principal investigator. Notes a Scale for the baseline and diary reports are different for these variables. Thus, scales were made comparable prior to the analysis. b Scale for the baseline and diary reports are different for this variable; assessing different aspects of stress, baseline stress measure assesses cumulative severity of daily stressors, and diary stress measure assesses number of daily stress events. ∗ < .05. ∗ p < .05. ∗ p < .05.",
